03959nam a22005415i 9780822395461DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223954617 a10.1515/97808223954612doi  a(DE-B1597)552503  a(OCoLC)1202623859  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBH301.C6bM38 2012 7aPHO0050002bisacsh04a700.11 aMavor, Carol, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlack and Blue :bThe Bruising Passion of Camera Lucida, La Jete, Sans soleil, and Hiroshima mon amour /cCarol Mavor. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b113 illustrations, including 18 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. First Things: Two Black and Blue Thoughts -- tAuthor's Note I. A Sewing Needle inside a Plastic and Rubber Suction Cup Sitting on a Watch Spring; or, An Object for Seeing Nothing -- tChapter 1. Elegy of Milk, in Black and Blue: The Bruising of La Chambre claire -- tChapter 2. "A" Is for Alice, for Amnesia, for Anamnesis: A Fairy Tale (Almost Blue) Called La Jetée -- tChapter 3. Happiness with a Long Piece of Black Leader: Chris Marker's Sans soleil -- tAuthor's Note II. She Wrote Me -- tChapter 4. "Summer Was inside the Marble": Alain Resnais's and Magurite Duras's Hiroshima mon amour -- tList of Illustrations -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAudacious and genre-defying, Black and Blue is steeped in melancholy, in the feeling of being blue, or, rather, black and blue, with all the literality of bruised flesh. Roland Barthes and Marcel Proust are inspirations for and subjects of Carol Mavor's exquisite, image-filled rumination on efforts to capture fleeting moments and to comprehend the incomprehensible. At the book's heart are one book and three films-Roland Barthes's Camera Lucida, Chris Marker's La Jetée and Sans soleil, and Marguerite Duras's and Alain Resnais's Hiroshima mon amour-postwar French works that register disturbing truths about loss and regret, and violence and history, through aesthetic refinement.Personal recollections punctuate Mavor's dazzling interpretations of these and many other works of art and criticism. Childhood memories become Proust's "small-scale contrivances," tiny sensations that open onto panoramas. Mavor's mother lost her memory to Alzheimer's, and Black and Blue is framed by the author's memories of her mother and effort to understand what it means to not be recognized by one to whom you were once so known.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aBlack. 0aBlue. 7aPhotography / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395461zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395461423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395461.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles